00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:49.930
OK, growing up, I didn't
have any role models really.

00:01:49.930 --> 00:01:53.410
It was a pretty scary
time in the '60s and '70s.

00:01:53.410 --> 00:01:56.740
And when I first moved here
to California from Chicago,

00:01:56.740 --> 00:01:58.370
I was about seven.

00:01:58.370 --> 00:02:01.630
And I rode my Stingray around.

00:02:01.630 --> 00:02:04.660
It looked just like that,
actually, and without a shirt

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:07.600
on until that just
wasn't OK anymore.

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:09.340
And what we did was--

00:02:09.340 --> 00:02:13.360
what I did was like beat
up boys after school.

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:15.790
We'd sneak out at night.

00:02:15.790 --> 00:02:18.560
We were just trouble,
my friends and I.

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:22.190
And, you know, it became
evident early on that--

00:02:22.190 --> 00:02:26.410
that I really liked
girls, and I was just--

00:02:26.410 --> 00:02:29.560
I would stand in front of the
mirror, and flex my muscles,

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:34.067
and I had two ideas in my head
that I was sure about, one

00:02:34.067 --> 00:02:35.650
that I was never
going to marry a man,

00:02:35.650 --> 00:02:38.600
and, two, that I was never
going to have a baby.

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:43.000
So those things ended up--
one of them ended up changing.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:43.840
But I was so--

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:47.110
I couldn't have been more
sure of anything in my life.

00:02:47.110 --> 00:02:51.820
Now, I also was a
big sandlot softball

00:02:51.820 --> 00:02:52.820
player, baseball player.

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:55.730
And I wanted to play
Little League so bad.

00:02:55.730 --> 00:02:57.010
And I was really good.

00:02:57.010 --> 00:02:59.380
And at that time-- and
this was pre Title IX.

00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:02.200
If you can imagine, they
didn't have to let girls play.

00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:04.420
So I wasn't allowed to play.

00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:06.160
So I joined a bobby
socks softball

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:09.580
team, which was called
the Great American Girls.

00:03:09.580 --> 00:03:13.960
And we had a coach who was
kind of a butchy mom type.

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:17.470
And we all had big brothers,
and we played so hard.

00:03:17.470 --> 00:03:20.140
We were sliding into home
and saying no batter.

00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:23.500
And we handily won
the championship,

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:26.740
and then at the end when they
were passing out the trophies,

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:28.870
it ended up that
they said, I'm sorry,

00:03:28.870 --> 00:03:31.360
but the great American
girls are disqualified.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:34.810
We're going to give the
trophy to the Buttercups

00:03:34.810 --> 00:03:37.060
because the Great
American Girls did not

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:39.110
play in a lady-like manner.

00:03:39.110 --> 00:03:41.050
So if you can
imagine a time when

00:03:41.050 --> 00:03:46.150
it was not OK to be
competitive or a tomboy--

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:51.410
so that was the message I was
getting pretty loud and clear.

00:03:51.410 --> 00:03:53.480
OK, so then when I
became a teenager,

00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:54.892
I applied to be a park ranger.

00:03:54.892 --> 00:03:56.350
And I became the
first park ranger.

00:03:56.350 --> 00:03:59.014
This is a shot of me with
a current park ranger

00:03:59.014 --> 00:04:00.430
that I ran into,
and I didn't have

00:04:00.430 --> 00:04:02.712
to wear the man pants
and the man boots.

00:04:02.712 --> 00:04:05.170
At the time, I could wear like
cute tennis shoes and really

00:04:05.170 --> 00:04:07.003
tight pants, like the
kind that you lay down

00:04:07.003 --> 00:04:12.070
and zip up and a big old shirt
with badges and a big key ring.

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:13.790
And I just thought
that was so cool.

00:04:13.790 --> 00:04:16.300
And I would stand around
daydreaming about the girl I

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:18.820
was crushed out on.

00:04:18.820 --> 00:04:20.120
Then I got to high school.

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:22.930
And I really tried
hard to be straight.

00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:25.700
You know, I had a very
feminine look, and I just--

00:04:25.700 --> 00:04:27.190
I got a lot of
attention from men,

00:04:27.190 --> 00:04:29.690
and so I just didn't
know what to do.

00:04:29.690 --> 00:04:33.880
So I tried really hard,
and it didn't work.

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:37.660
When I got to college,
I went to a summer

00:04:37.660 --> 00:04:43.120
in Europe, where I met
another woman who was also

00:04:43.120 --> 00:04:48.036
had never been with a girl, and
we both were stumbling around.

00:04:48.036 --> 00:04:49.160
It was a very awkward time.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:51.140
But we got through it.

00:04:51.140 --> 00:04:54.430
And then after that, I finally
moved to San Francisco, where

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:56.700
I finally found my people.

00:04:56.700 --> 00:04:59.940
And we lived on
Castro Street in 1982.

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:02.760
I met this woman, and
we started a family

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:03.930
after about seven years.

00:05:06.780 --> 00:05:07.680
We each had a boy.

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:12.520
My brother was the
donor for the older boy.

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:16.590
And then she couldn't get
pregnant again the second time

00:05:16.590 --> 00:05:18.510
we wanted to, and
so I had to step up,

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:23.100
and it was terribly difficult
as an athlete to be pregnant.

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:26.040
And that picture on the
bottom is my son and I.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:27.090
We look exactly the same.

00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:30.330
I gotta say, it's one of
the most empowering things

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.380
that I've ever been
through, like an Amazon,

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:35.490
like to give birth, like, here
I was a little kid thinking

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:39.510
I can never do this, and it
ended up being really awesome

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:43.800
except for ruining my body,
and he cried for five-years

00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:44.790
straight pretty much.

00:05:47.021 --> 00:05:49.020
But when he got a little
older-- and it was cool

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:51.360
because I couldn't have
really had a baby with a man.

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:54.480
I wasn't really that
great with infants.

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:57.600
And my ex partner loved
to just stay home.

00:05:57.600 --> 00:05:58.494
I worked really hard.

00:05:58.494 --> 00:05:59.910
I was so happy to
go back to work,

00:05:59.910 --> 00:06:02.070
and she took care
of the infants.

00:06:02.070 --> 00:06:05.190
And so they're really good kids.

00:06:05.190 --> 00:06:07.850
So then at this
time, we head to--

00:06:07.850 --> 00:06:09.570
OK, we were the first
wave of parents.

00:06:12.150 --> 00:06:14.280
Other people were having
children that were older

00:06:14.280 --> 00:06:16.320
than us, but there was
no real group of parents.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:18.090
So we were in San
Francisco at this time

00:06:18.090 --> 00:06:24.300
when we had like a gay PTA, and
we had a very inclusive campus,

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:26.220
and it was just-- it
was nice, you know?

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:28.140
But we still had
to do this thing

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:31.260
where we adopted each other's
kids because we couldn't

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:34.350
be legally the parent
of our own child-- or I

00:06:34.350 --> 00:06:37.350
couldn't be the legal parent
of the child she gave birth to

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:38.190
and vice versa.

00:06:38.190 --> 00:06:41.760
So we had to literally give
up our children to each other,

00:06:41.760 --> 00:06:43.165
and the judge would just--

00:06:43.165 --> 00:06:44.790
I remember we had to
go to court twice,

00:06:44.790 --> 00:06:47.020
and he would just like
point at us and say,

00:06:47.020 --> 00:06:48.853
are you sure you want
to give up your child?

00:06:48.853 --> 00:06:51.870
And I'm like, oh my god,
it was really intense.

00:06:51.870 --> 00:06:53.010
And then we got married.

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:55.320
We went down to City Hall.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:57.240
Gavin Newsom made
it OK to go down.

00:06:57.240 --> 00:07:01.500
And we ran down there,
and it was exciting.

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:03.570
And my youngest
was eight, and he

00:07:03.570 --> 00:07:06.117
was like, oh, yay, this means
you'll be married forever.

00:07:06.117 --> 00:07:07.200
You'll always be together.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:09.270
And, unfortunately,
that wasn't the case.

00:07:09.270 --> 00:07:11.610
But what happened that
was cool about that

00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:14.850
was that he-- you know,
he just felt so validated

00:07:14.850 --> 00:07:16.440
by us being able to be married.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:19.355
So I feel like that's
such an important--

00:07:19.355 --> 00:07:20.730
it's just an
important thing when

00:07:20.730 --> 00:07:24.890
you think about the whole
right for same-sex marriage,

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:29.490
that the kids are the ones that
are being hurt by it so much.

00:07:29.490 --> 00:07:36.090
So we got our marriage
certificate mailed back

00:07:36.090 --> 00:07:37.650
to us after about--

00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:40.320
I think it was less than a month
later, it arrived in the mail

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:44.460
as annulled, because
the law didn't stick.

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:47.940
So then at that point,
we moved to Marin County.

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:49.410
That's where I grew
up, as you saw.

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:52.950
And I wanted my kids to
have a more rural existence.

00:07:52.950 --> 00:07:58.790
So I brought them to Marin,
and my oldest came home saying,

00:07:58.790 --> 00:08:02.970
oh, god, mommy, why is everybody
saying you're so gay, you fag.

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:04.440
And he just didn't understand.

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:06.109
It was shocking for him.

00:08:06.109 --> 00:08:08.400
And I was like, well, we're
not living in San Francisco

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:09.483
it's not a bubble anymore.

00:08:09.483 --> 00:08:13.872
So he became the kind of kid
who told his friends, look,

00:08:13.872 --> 00:08:16.330
I'm not going to be your friend
if you say stuff like that,

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:17.460
and you know, I don't know.

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:22.110
I got-- I got motivated
to go into the schools

00:08:22.110 --> 00:08:26.220
and become a speaker for
the LGBT Speakers Bureau,

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:29.010
to be a coach for the
Little League team,

00:08:29.010 --> 00:08:32.940
to coach for soccer, and just
be visible and like help them.

00:08:32.940 --> 00:08:34.614
I mean, like,
things would happen,

00:08:34.614 --> 00:08:37.030
like, I'd have kids over for
the soccer party and I'd say,

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:38.900
Timmy, what are you
doing out there?

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:41.679
And he'd say, oh, we're playing
smear the queer, you know,

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:42.720
in the backyard.

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:44.070
I'm like, what?

00:08:44.070 --> 00:08:45.180
And, you know, so--

00:08:45.180 --> 00:08:46.890
and it just went on and on.

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:49.560
Some of the dads would say, wow,
you really remind me of Ellen,

00:08:49.560 --> 00:08:50.340
and I'm like, why?

00:08:50.340 --> 00:08:51.256
I don't look like her.

00:08:51.256 --> 00:08:53.520
And we just had--

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:56.940
there was a lot of
homophobia in Marin,

00:08:56.940 --> 00:08:59.850
and I think about all the
people in the outlying areas

00:08:59.850 --> 00:09:00.370
right now.

00:09:00.370 --> 00:09:03.430
I mean, we live
in such a bubble.

00:09:03.430 --> 00:09:08.640
So I got the idea to write this
book, which is about lesbian

00:09:08.640 --> 00:09:11.570
heroes of my generation.

00:09:11.570 --> 00:09:15.060
And the women that they
looked up to weren't--

00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:16.470
it wasn't like they were bad.

00:09:16.470 --> 00:09:20.400
It was just that the role
models weren't very positive.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:24.150
So they passed a law called,
the Fair Education Act

00:09:24.150 --> 00:09:27.000
kind of recently, and it
really got me excited,

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.310
like, this was something
that I could contribute to.

00:09:29.310 --> 00:09:31.680
I could-- I'm a graphic
designer, and an editor,

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:32.430
and a curator.

00:09:32.430 --> 00:09:35.450
And I have a huge circle
of people that I know.

00:09:35.450 --> 00:09:38.310
And I just thought I can make a
really fun book that teenagers

00:09:38.310 --> 00:09:39.610
are going to love.

00:09:39.610 --> 00:09:45.527
And so what this law does is it
requires LGBT education as far

00:09:45.527 --> 00:09:47.610
as history and social
studies in the public school

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:49.290
curriculum in California.

00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:52.050
And right now, there
it's not really

00:09:52.050 --> 00:09:53.770
like the curriculum exists.

00:09:53.770 --> 00:09:56.760
It's not like really
there's resources for them.

00:09:56.760 --> 00:09:59.340
I attended a
symposium last week,

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:02.284
or two weeks ago,
where we got in a room

00:10:02.284 --> 00:10:04.200
and did a whole big think
tank about how we're

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:05.470
going to get this to happen.

00:10:05.470 --> 00:10:08.250
And it's clearly
a couple years out

00:10:08.250 --> 00:10:10.050
before there'll really
be a lot of things

00:10:10.050 --> 00:10:11.610
available to students.

00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:16.320
And especially public schools
don't have a lot of resources

00:10:16.320 --> 00:10:17.640
to spend on stuff like this.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:20.040
So I got it in my head that
I wanted to make this book

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:23.010
and donate it to the
public high schools

00:10:23.010 --> 00:10:26.130
in Marin, San Francisco,
Oakland, and Berkeley.

00:10:26.130 --> 00:10:29.520
So what I did was I
decided to go crowdfunding.

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:31.710
And I got to say, if
you're a little insecure,

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:35.940
and you have a full time job,
this is a brutal way to go.

00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:39.150
I was-- it was so excruciating.

00:10:39.150 --> 00:10:40.140
I went at it--

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:44.070
two different runs at it,
each for about $10,000.

00:10:44.070 --> 00:10:46.560
And, no, the money's
not all from my family.

00:10:46.560 --> 00:10:49.840
It really did get spread
out amongst about 200 people

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:52.380
at an average of
about $100 each.

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:56.090
It required, you know, live
Facebook videos, you know, yay,

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:57.860
you know, so scary.

00:10:57.860 --> 00:10:59.790
Anyway, so I got all
that money, and then

00:10:59.790 --> 00:11:01.920
I was able to print
the books, and I

00:11:01.920 --> 00:11:04.620
was able to deliver them to
the 48 public high schools,

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:07.750
and it serves about
49,000 students now.

00:11:07.750 --> 00:11:09.440
And these schools
have invited me in

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:11.370
to talk in their classroom.

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:14.670
I've been able to just
share with these kids

00:11:14.670 --> 00:11:15.850
and hear their stories.

00:11:15.850 --> 00:11:19.080
And I had one girl
come up to me just

00:11:19.080 --> 00:11:20.760
in tears saying,
oh, my god, I can't

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:22.140
believe you're really here.

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:23.150
And she had--

00:11:23.150 --> 00:11:24.780
I had these books
kind of sprinkled

00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:27.087
around some bookstores
too like in the Castro.

00:11:27.087 --> 00:11:28.920
And she said, I got
your book in the Castro.

00:11:28.920 --> 00:11:30.360
And I'm-- I'm just--

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:31.770
I can't believe it, you know?

00:11:31.770 --> 00:11:33.040
She was hugging me and crying.

00:11:33.040 --> 00:11:36.400
It was like so gratifying.

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:39.870
So I wanted to show you
